The winter passed.  Storms seen earlier in the season did not come after the new year and the farmers predicted a good season.  The days warmed and Tannor's Stand returned to being the bustling little town it was known to be.  Farming was generally better near Nexi, and Tannor's Stand was just ten miles from the nearest one in Rimdale Forest.<br>
Nexi were good for many things, as those in the Caeban of the Nine Pale Hands were aware.  The Rimdale Nexus had remained stable over the winter, as it had for as long as they could remember and the gathering of Crafters moved on about their business.<br>
That business was, for the most part, mundane.  Helping farmers with crops or pests, studying the patterns of flora and fauna in the area, predictions, seeings and minor politics.  Mundane.  And all left to L'cia's subordinates.  She was tired of it.<br>
<br>
L'cia longed for what she saw as the greater glory of the old days, the old ways.  She hoped, with this Guptras Den by her side, she might play a part in restoring the power to the Caebans of Andar.  Patience was the key, she knew this.  Guptras always saw fit to remind her as well.  No matter, she had many, many good years left.  Her power still grew, slowly, but grew nonetheless.  Her caeban needed rejuvenation though if it was to regain its status as a Greater Caeban.  The Nine Pale Hands needed new blood, new apprentices to carry out her plan.  T'ara did not share in her ideals, but of course she didn't know her Mistress' thoughts either, she was an innocent with no idea of what her Mistress' dealings were.  She did as she was instructed, which L'cia valued greatly.  T'ara had been set with the task of finding young women who would be suitable for apprenticeship as the years went by.  Because they were not allowed specifically to recruit members from Tannor's Stand, they only looked for those who would be drawn naturally to an understanding, caring group that could give them the feeling of self-esteem.  A group that made them feel wanted.  This way they would grow slowly, without attracting the attention of the town elders, and bring in those more suitable for L'cia's plans.<br>
<br>
Several girls had been marked as the type the caeban sought.  Their home-lives were not what they should be, or they were more rebellious than most children, and they were watched.<br>
The druid, Mara, was also watched.  She had never bothered the caeban, never even paid them attention, but there she was, planted firmly between the caeban's hidden location and Tannor's Stand.<br>
Mara had never taken part in politics, never made her voice heard in any situation.  To most townsfolk she was merely a curiosity, witch to some, kindly old woman to others, but none bothered her and most were friendly.  The only townsfolk she dealt with besides the merchants she patronized were the children.<br>
The same type of children the caeban sought.  Yes, she would bear watching.<br>
<br>
Mara was dismayed to learn Lora had not attended any type of schooling since leaving Miera Kiy.  Tannor's Stand did not have an organized school, so the druid took it upon herself to instruct the child.<br>
Loreana was a good student, hungry for knowledge though her moods didn't always permit the steady, paced study normal to schooling.  Mara didn't mind, teaching whatever the girl was eager for at the time.  Lora loved to read and Mara did her best to provide her with books on everything from politics to fiction.  When Lora wasn't in the mood to read, there were more than enough topics that grabbed her interest.  She loved to watch and question every move that Mara or Greeneyes made whether they were cooking or creating the potions, poultices, and components they used to work Gaervalen's magic.<br>
<br>
Loreana and Greeneyes always maintained a wary distance from each other, but what they couldn't share up close they compensated for in other ways.  They talked, they revealed to each other what they saw or heard in the forest and meadow nearby.  The two grew close in mind and spirit as they shared the wonders of the nature and magic they learned.<br>
Times were not always good.  Loreana still suffered from intense nightmares she could never remember.  At home, Jerem complained about her cries when she woke, shaking and scared.  Merrie paid less and less attention to Lora as the widow rode the waves of depression she still suffered from Brian's death and Jerem's bouts of drunken moodiness.  Whether he was happy with Merrie or angry, there never seemed to be a place Loreana fit in her mother's life.  Merrie rarely even asked where Loreana had been, even when she stayed at Mara's for several days straight.<br>
<br>
When summer came, Loreana and Cessara would go to the spring to talk and dream.  They still played with friends and shared the secrets young girls shared.  Cess was thirteen now and as summer came she started showing an interest in the boys.  Lora didn't think much of it, but it didn't bother her.  Most of the boys were a pain and she didn't understand why Cess always liked to talk to some of them in the market.  One of them, Samuel, especially attracted Cess's attention.  He just annoyed Lora, he was thirteen and too impressed with himself.  It would take forever to drag Cess away from him.  One day, Samuel offered to buy Cess a pastry but not Lora and she stalked away to Mara's in a huff.<br>
<br>
Cess and Lora lay side by side looking up at the clouds.  The stream gurgled happily nearby as the girls listened in silence at the world around them.<br>
&quot;I met someone a few days ago.  A woman.&quot;<br>
&quot;So,&quot; Lora replied, unimpressed.<br>
&quot;She knows magic.&quot;<br>
&quot;Mara knows magic, so does Greeneyes.  They're teaching me.&quot;<br>
&quot;She said she could teach me too.&quot;<br>
&quot;I thought your mom didn't like magic.&quot;<br>
&quot;She doesn't like Mara.  She never said anything about magic...not exactly.&quot;<br>
&quot;So what can she teach you?&quot;<br>
&quot;Look.&quot;  Cess sat up and waited for Lora to roll her head towards her.  &quot;She already taught me something.  'Something simple', she said.&quot;<br>
Cess held the palm of her hand open, concentrated for a moment and blew.  A small candle flame sprang to life from the center of her hand.<br>
&quot;Wow!&quot;  Now Lora was impressed.<br>
&quot;It's not hot.  You can't burn yourself or light a candle with it or anything.  She says its good for seeing at night in your room or something.&quot;  The flame went out and Cess frowned.  &quot;I have to concentrate to keep it going.&quot;<br>
&quot;That's neat.  I'm just learning things like healing sick plants and making stuff to put on cuts.&quot;  Lora shifted slightly.  &quot;Do you think she could teach me too?&quot;<br>
&quot;I don't know.  She said she likes to teach and she did ask if I had any friends.&quot;<br>
Lora punched her playfully in the arm.  &quot;So, Friend, ask her for me.&quot;<br>
Cess poked her on the forehead.  &quot;Ask her yourself.  I'm gonna see her tomorrow at midday over behind Pretcher's place.  You can come with me.&quot;<br>
&quot;Oh thank you,&quot; Lora said with playful sarcasm.  &quot;I think I will.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;You missed your studies yesterday Loreana.  What happened?&quot;<br>
Lora looked at Mara in surprise.  &quot;Oops.  I'm sorry.  I forgot.  I was out with Cess.&quot;  She left out the part where she and Cess had met with the woman Tannara.  She was neat, and very nice.  Tannara had brought along a basket of bread, cheese, dried beef, and a very good fruit juice of some kind.  She had talked with the girls for hours and didn't mind Loreana coming along at all.  The woman was eager to teach them magic and other things she knew.  Like Mara, she talked about the forest and animals, but the part the girls like the best were the stories she told about the fairies and tree sprites and spirits that made the forest a mysterious and wondrous place.<br>
Tannara said she could talk to the spirits.  Lora was a little skeptical, but Tannara said that she might show them sometime.<br>
When the sun started to set and they said their good-byes.  Cess and Lora walked back home talking of dancing fairies, shy dryads and magic.<br>
&quot;Ok dear, we can get to it later perhaps.  For now, how about helping me make those turnovers I told you about?<br>
Lora hopped excitedly and nodded even as her thoughts strayed to fairy dust and candle flames you could hold in your hand.<br>
<br>
Mara scented something was wrong when Loreana asked about wood spirits.<br>
&quot;Are they the children of Gaervalen also?&quot; she asked, curious if Mara would teach her about them as Tannara had.<br>
&quot;Not so much children as those who have strayed from his care,&quot; she replied carefully, wondering where the girl had heard this.<br>
&quot;So they were, but aren't now?&quot; Lora pushed the question.<br>
Mara nodded slowly.  &quot;Some call them the Lost Children.  Many are tricksters, or angry spirits, some just mischievous, but few can be trusted.&quot;  Mara turned nonchalantly away, &quot;Where have you heard of them?&quot;<br>
Loreana wasn't fooled and decided the topic wasn't a safe one.  &quot;From a few of the girls.  I thought you'd know.&quot;  She turned and skipped out the door, effectively ending the conversation.<br>
Mara turned back to the herbs she was grinding.  The druid suspected that is was not Loreana's friends who had told the girl about these things.  No, her suspicions led her in an entirely different direction.<br>
<br>
